@node inst "Installation of KController"

@{b}Installation@{ub}
------------

Copy the file kc-start.prefs to envarc:. THAT`S ALL!

@endnode

@node winbar "The WinBar"
@{b}The WinBar@{ub}
----------

If you want to use the WinBar only, you need not read the rest of this doc.
(but read @{"Installation" link inst}, but that`s all)
Start KernelController with the option "winbar" (e.g. "kc:kc winbar"),
or double click on the WB-icon. 
The program opens a new bar at the bottom of the WB-Screen with all opened
windows. Click on the window you want to put into the front of the screen.
If you want a menu with some commands hold the shift key down and click on
any window.
The commands of the menu:

-Zip Window
Maximises or minimises the window (like the gadget in the titlebar of the
window)

-Win to back
Puts the window into the background of the screen

-Close Window
Closes the window
WARNING!! This command kills the window, but not the task, this may corrupt
your system!!!

-Kill Task
Kills the task of the window
WARNING!!! This command do not quit the task, it kills the task at any time,
this may corrupt your system!!!

To open the start menu, click on the START-button. Move the Cursor to
"Programs". In the new Window are the Items and
another Groups. Click on the name of the program with the right mousebutton
to edit the icon. A click with the left button starts the program.

@endnode
@node tasks "The TaskKiller"

@{b}The Tasks-Window@{ub}
----------------

This function opens a window with all waiting tasks of the system.
You can chose a task and press "kill" to kill this task, BUT BE CAREFULL,
it may corrupt your system!
Start KernelController with the option "tasks" (e.g. "kc:kc tasks").
If you only want to use this function, you need not read the rest of this
doc.

@endnode
@node misc "KController CLI"

@{b}The Commands@{ub}
------------

After starting KernelController (e.g. "kc:kc") you see a new prompt like
this:

Workbench Screen*AmigaShell#>
\\______  ______/|\\___  ___/|
       \\/       |    \\/    |
    current     | current  `viewed if you are on the gadget level
    screen      | window
                |
                `viewed if you are on the window level


If there is no "*", you are on the screen-level, otherwise you are on the
window-level, and a "#" shows that you are on the gadget-level.

The commands:

?: shows all available commands

list: if you are on the screen-level it lists some data of the current
screen, and all opened windows on this screen

enter: opens the next level (screen-level->window-level,
window-level->gadget-level)

next: opens the next element on a level (on the screen-level the next
screen, on the window-level the next window, on the gadget-level the next
gadget)

core: opens the first element of the current level

edit: in this version you can only edit the position of the current gadget
(if you are on the gadget-level)

back: opens the previous level (gadget-level->window-level,
window-level->screen-level)

view: if you are on the gadget-level it shows the current gadget and opens
an Info-Window with some date of the gadget

all: shows all opened Info-Windows (see command "view")

paint: if you are on the window-level you can paint in the current window

-move the cursor to the position and press SPACE to paint
-press c to change the color
-press s to save the changes (you can load this file with the command
"load")
-press q to quit

move: use to scroller-gadgets to move the current gadget (if you are on the
gadget-level), or move the cursor to the new position of the gadget and press
SPACE (you can hold down the key), press q to quit this command

close: closes all opened Info-Windows (see command "view")

delete: closes the current screen (with ALL windows), the current window or
the current gadget

winbar: see "The WinBar"

tasks: see "The Tasks-Window"

quit: i think you know what it means

@endnode



